column168: A Florida Rock and Tank Lines driver was unloading the last compartment of gasoline into the 10,000 gallon above ground tank when it spilled out the top. column169: Florida Rock and Tank Lines has reviewed delivery procedures to ensure only accurate information is provided for tank capacity.

column168: Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to the customer storage tank that was located inside a building.  Dr said he was using no more than 10 psi.  When the hose jumped indicating the cargo tank was empty, he closed the valve on the trailer and disconnected the air supply hose.   He waited for product to skim the inside of the trailer (to minimize heel), and then cracked open the valve 1/2 turn for a few seconds to clear the discharge hose and then closed it.  Sometime during this process, about 1 quart of product sprayed out of the customer tank on to the side of the tank and into the containment area.  The plant operator was inside the building and notified the driver.
column169: it does not seem that the driver used an excess of pressure.  Maybe this product could be pumped off?  Or the tank vented in a different way or not filled as full?

column168: July 6, 2012: During a routine inspection, FRA Hazardous Material Inspector R. Dedow detected an odor originating from tank car TILX 19263, containing the residue of Alcohols, NOS, while inspecting the empty unity train that had been pulled from Motiva, Sewaren, NJ.    The car was set out from the train and returned back to the originating facility (approximately 2 miles from where the car was inspected).  Shipper inspected car inside their facility and noted a crimped manway cover gasket.  Gasket was replaced with new in kind, and the manway cover was closed and secured as required, allowing the car to be transported back to original destination.

column168: 33 coolers tendered by Arctic couriers on behalf of Pilot air Freight. Shipping representative said "NO DG".  At time of Screening Agent Beverly noticed 1 cooler had an "E" exepted qty sticker with info of class 3, un1230. Thinking sticker could be old, she opened up cooler to find 2 white boxes with Corrosive Class 8 Sticker. Inside boxes vials, and glass jars labeled hydrochloric acid.  Shipment set aside, shipper adv we would not load and shipment would be held.  Lead agent Made' Cronkhite opened all 33 coolers 13jul. Contents:    -22 coolers contained empty brown bottles and small clear empty bottles  -1 cooler with 15bottles labeled hydrochloric acid, looks like small qty.   -1cooler with 1 bottle hydrochloric acid and 11 empty bottles   -1cooler with  13bottles containing hydrochloric acid, looks like small qty.   -1 cooler with 14 bottles marked hydrochloric acid, looks like small qty.   -1 cooler with 12 bottles marked hydrochloric acid   -1 cooler with 6 empty bottles, and 6 bottles marked hydrochloric acid   -1 cooler with white box containing 72 small vials 25ml hydrochloric acid each.   -1 cooler containing 1 box with glass vials all FULL of liquid , hydrochloric acid.     Shipment, set aside. Spoke to Ron Fink at AS DG office for discussion. Advised to file report.   Brian from pilot air adv situation and we would hold pending report to FAA.   Last night spoke to shipper/packing agent and he was surprised of any issue.  Agreed that 2 coolers possibly mislabled since no UN1230. Beleives other coolers packaged in correct quantities acceptable without other needed labeling.
column169: Suggest packaging agent make a detailed list of items in shipment/per container. to give to courier service.  Courier agent should double check that any labels on packages are questioned before acceptance from shipper, and before tendering shipment to air carrier.

A Tractor-trailer loaded with 22 sac’s of UN 3077 was involved in a traffic accident that caused a minor release of the product inside the trailer.  The local law enforcement required the tow company to move the trailer, while moving the trailer it rolled down an embankment causing further product to be released.        Cleanup was delayed one day due a NASCAR Race and DOT would not let one lane to be closed.    On Sunday, while the tow company was removing the trailer from the embankment, the trailer split open under the force of the tow cables.  An estimated 4 super sac’s were damaged releasing product.    A Super Sucker Vacuum Unit was mobilized to the site to collect the product.  A total of ten 55-gallon drums of product were containerized.  A small site excavation was conducted for remove some diesel fuel contamination from the area    All waste will be disposed of at the permitted facility.

column168: On 07/01/2012, at 1050 hours, personnel in the CSXT Montgomery Terminal discovered TAEX 182, a loaded tank car of Molten Phenol, leaking from the washout plate. The car was isolated and the shipper Sabic, local fire department, Alabama Department Environmental Management, NRC, and CHEMTREC report # 2012-07-01-00031 were notified.  USES  United States Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from the washout plate securement bolts. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Jack Lowery, 812-480-4868. Contractor personnel secured the bolts and decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car is awaiting the shipper to file an OTMA prior to movement to final destination. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be filed.     NARRI: 5(5+5)(2)=100  Cause Code: 632
column169: No additional comments.

The contractor neutralized the spilled material, applied absorbents and worked them in. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

On 07/02/2012 at 0545 hours, train crew Y39101 was making a switching movement and failed to properly align the C-yard wye switch. Y39101 ran through the C-yard wye switch that was positioned against his movement, and then made a reverse movement causing rail car GETX 2329 to travel into two different tracks. This action caused five rail cars to overturn, resulting in a breach to UTLX 57885, caused by one of the wheel sets. A total of 22,022 gallons of product was released into the surrounding ballast. column168: Tank car TILX303199 was found to be leaking in the Kansas City Southern (KCS) Kansas City Yard at 1:15 PM. Release originated from defective hardened pressure relief device (PRD) O-ring. Responder replaced o-ring with same material (Viton) as installed by shipper, secured, and shipped on. The shipper could not advise responders on O-ring compatability type.     Tank car found later leaking from PRD while at Roodhouse, IL. Responder concluded shipper applied incompatible Oring type and re-applied neoprene O-ring.     File Note Item 19 - the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27 - Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: DURING INSPECTION ON 7/12/2012 FOUND VAPOR LEAK FROM RAILCAR MAN-WAY DOME LID. INSPECTED AND SAW GASKET DETERIORATE AND BULGING OUTWARD. FRA GRAY FLORES AND PUC TOM HERVEY WERE ON THE SCENE AND INSPECTED. FOUND THE GASKET WAS ALMOST COMPLETELY GONE. RE-CLOSED THE LID. CALL FREMONT FIRE DEPARTMENT. THEY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. INSPECTED. FREMONT FIRE FOLLOWED MSDS PROTOCOLS AND DAWNED MASKS AND OTHER PPE'S. FREMONT FIRE TURNED THE EVENT INTO A TRAINING/REAL LIVE EVENT. WE GAVE THEM A GASKET WHICH THEY INSTALLED. THEY TESTED THE AIR WITH THERE FOUR GAS ANALYZER FOR LEAKS. NONE WERE DETECTED. WE CALLED THE SHIPPER OF THE RAILCAR TO HAVE A TRAINED CREW COME OUT AND RECHECK AND REPLACE GASKET WITH CORRECT ONE BEFORE IT SHIPS. (ASAP)
column169: WE RECOMMEND THAT THE RAILROAD DO MORE THOROUGH INSPECTION BEFORE EXCEPTING CARS AND SHIPPERS NEED TO INSPECT MORE THOROUGHLY BEFORE RELEASING TO RAILROAD.

column168: A rolloff box arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  While checking in, it was noticed that liquid was leaking from under the rear door.  The container was immediately moved into containment and absorbent pads were placed under the dripping area.  The driver donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and tightened the ratchets, stopping the leak.  The absorbent pads were placed into the container and the load was accepted into the ten day storage lot without further incident.
column169: The driver should have checked the ratchets more carefully when picking up the load.  They were not tightened enough and casued the liquid that had separated from the sludge to drip out of the back door.  The driver is to be retrained on proper closure of rolloff boxes.

column168: Prox 42037 was noticed by CP Employees to be hissing from the top of the railcar, Wenck(Contractor for CP) was called in to investigat the railcar, upon investigation it was determined that the Vaccum Relief valve was not sealing, the valve was removed and it was noted that the Quad oring was cracked in several places, a temporry repair was made on the valve to stop the leak until a new one could be located to replace the faulty one. Rescar car replaced the valve on July 12, 2012. after passing the buble test the car was released to the railroad.
column169: Look into the cracking quad rings and have loading facilty if possible check oring before loading car

column168: PROX 042039 was noticed to be hissing by CP Personnel from the top of the railcar.Wenck (Contractor for CP) was called to investigate the railcar, Upon investigation, it was determined that the leak was comming from the vacuum relief valve. The valve was pulled and it was noted that the sealing quad oring was cracked and that the valve seat was sevearly rusted and pitted. a new quad oring was installed to stop the leak and Rescar was called to come out and replace the valve. currently waiting on Rescar to resorce a new valve and install. No Liquid was released , only vapors.
column169: Loading facilities should check the vacuum relif valves when ever posible for condition of valve seat and quad oring quality.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A FRA Inspector reported residue tank car BNSF 880210 leaking from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) in the railyard. BNSF operating personnel were notified and a containment receptacle was placed under BNSF 880210. A mechanical responder reported tool tightening the bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) two full turns which stopped the residue product dripping. An environmental response contractor applied Micro Blaze to observed ground spillage and removed the containment receptacle with its contents earmarked for appropriate disposal.     A previous inspection of BNSF 880210 by BNSF's Director of Hazardous Material in the morning of July 4, 2012 revealed no securement exceptions and no observed leakage from the BOV-BOC. The top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod was closed and secure at that time.    BNSF 880210 is awaiting furtherance to a repair facility.

column168: We were contacted by the TSA when the passenger's bag set off an alarm that indicated there may be undeclared hazardous materials inside the bag. There was a strong acetone smell eminating from the bag. When the duffle bag was unzipped, some of the liquid contents from a couple of containers inside the bags had spilled out. The duffle bag had been wrapped in plastic, so the spilled liquid was contained inside the bag. It was determined that the contents inside the bag were nail polish paint. The nail polish paint had been bottled in medicine bottles of different sizes (totalling approximately 452 Fluid ounces). These bottles had been taped back and sealed to desguise their true content. At first sight it gave the impression that the bottles contained the medicine portrayed on the boxes and labels, but after close inspection, it was discovered that the original content had been replaced with nail polish paint. The items were confiscated and reported to the FAA. The spill remained contained in the bag.
column169: The government and the airlines should partner together to educate the traveling public on the danger of hazardous material transportation.

column168: During a BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard, entrained tank car ACFX 79721 was reported with fresh product on its side shell that emanating from the top fitting area.  A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and immediately inspected ACFX 79721. The responder reported finding the liquid valve closed but loose on its threaded pipe flange connection.  The responder tool tightened the loose valve on its threaded connection with a pipe wrench. Afterwards, the responder noticed a small amount of liquid escaping from the liquid line's bolted pipe flange connection below the valve. The tool tight flange bolt nuts were removed to inspect the flange gasket. The flange gasket appeared 'flattened' and sealant was applied around the flange connection to ensure a good seal at this bolted flange connection. The flange bolt nuts were reapplied and tool tightened. The valve connection was monitored and no further product leakage was observed. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was noted. Intact shipper seal SLS JACKSON, NE 0026161at the valve housing cover was replaced with BNSF seal 06157446.

column168: Driver noticed the methanol leaking from the center floor of his trailer while he was traveling southbound on the New Jersey turnpike.  He pulled over on the side of the road just north of exit 12.  The nose of the trailer was loaded with a load rack on its side to keep the first 4 feet of the trailer without a tote in the nose, then there was 1 tote loaded in the middle behind the load rack, then the next 6 totes were loaded side by side on the trailer.  there was no evidence that lack of blocking caused any impact to the spouts to cause them to leak.  There were 2 leaking stainless steel totes, with approximately 375 gallons in each.  The two totes lost approximately 1/3 of the liquid contained within for an approximate total of 250 gallons.  All of the spouts were facing the nose of the trailer.      Fire department on scene during cleanup procedures completed by outside vendor.  NJ report #12-07-11-05074-46    Field activity (vendor) report available upon request.

column168: Loaded tank car (TILX 191653) was reported to be releasing product a rate of one drip per five seconds from the bottom outlet valve. The shipper responded to handle mitigation of the incident.  Preliminary assessment of the valve found an imperfection in the valve seat allowing for a slow release to occur.  It was also noted the BOV cap was tool tight, however, it appeared the cap did not seat properly allowing product to be pushed out of the cap. The leak was mitigated by adding Teflon tape to the BOV cap until the car could be unloaded at its origin facility.

column168: July 18, 2012: At approximately 8:10am, during a routine patrol through Conrail's Port Richmond Yard, Philadelphia, PA, NS Special Agent A. Ingram discovered tank car UTLX 201286, load, Gasoline, to be leaking down the sides of the car from the top in a cascading fashion.  SA Ingram notified CR, the operator of the yard.    CR Risk Management dispatched emergency response contractor Hepaco-React to inspect and mitigate.  Further inspection by Hepaco-React noted the 3" liquid valve (threaded onto the mounting plate) had been removed/stolen; and the closure plug for the 1" air valve was removed but valve was closed.  Leak originating from the opening created by the removal of the liquid valve.    Hepaco-React opened the air valve to vent off pressure, which allowed the car to cease leaking.  The missing 3" stainless liquid valve was replaced in kind (supplied by Hepaco-React); and the air valve closure plug was reapplied tool tight.      Ground effected by release of product, estimated at 100 gallons, was removed by Hepaco-React, and is staged at the site for eventual removal/disposal.    CR will apply for OTMA request to have the car shipped to original destination, Kinder Morgan, Philadelphia, PA, without benefit of valves being leak tested, so the car can be unloaded and further leak tested on site, or, have the car forwarded to a, as yet, designated shop for required leak test of the newly applied valve.    Suspected vandalism is being investigated by NS Police.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  When the dock personnel began to unload the trailer, they noticed a strong odor and saw a small amount of liquid on the trailer floor and also dripped onto the ground.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and, after monitoring the air, entered the trailer.  A 2" cap on the left front corner of the container was not secured causing liquid to leak out. The closure was properly tightened and the shipment was unloaded without further incident.

column168: Railcar GATX 14142 was switched in the Syngenta Crop Protection facility, located in Omaha, NE, at approximately 13:00 on July 10, 2012.  The railcar was moved into position at the facility for unloading on Wednesday, July 11, 2012.  Operations personnel began the process of inspection and equipment set-up when they noticed spray / splatter on the top & sides of the railcar.  The manway & dip-tube dome seals were in place and not broken.  During the initial investigation, it appears some material was released from the pressure relief valve on the top of the railcar.  The product on the railcar was completely dry, indicating the release occurred during transport to the facility.  It does not appear the pressure relief valve failed, but rather, the release could be attributed to excessive / sudden movement of the car during transport to the Syngenta facility.  Therefore, the cause of failure was identified as 'Human Error'.
column169: Railcar was unloaded at the facility & was delivered to Nebraska Railcar Cleaning Company for decontamination and verification the pressure relief valve is not damaged.

column168: On July 5, 2012, at 2306 hours, personnel in the CSXT Radnor yard discovered UTLX 200587, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Evonik Degussa Corp., was notified via CHEMTREC report #2012-07-05-00007. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the gasket below the continuous vent to be bad. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Calvin Dixon 251-443-4241. Contractor personnel inspected the gasket and secured the bolts for the vent assembly and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0)  =  100    Cause Code: 715
column169: No additional recommendations.

column168: On July 14, 2012 at 1045 hours, a car inspector at Selkirk yard reported LTCX 1616, a load of Argon, Refrigerated Liquid, UN1951, venting continuously from the B-R side valve cabinet. The tank car was isolated and a CSX HazMat Sentinel responded to inspect the car and found the B-R side vapor valve was open 1 turn. The shipper, Praxair, Inc. was notified via Chemtrec, report #2012-07-14-00053. The issue identified was discussed with shipper representative, Mr. William Greene, 716.879.7245. The CSX Sentinel closed the vapor valve  and the venting stopped. The valve cabinet was re-sealed and the tank car was released for disposition.  This incident did NOT require a special switch move.    NARRI 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause Code: 379
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On July 16, 2012 at 1857 hours, a CSXT emergency response contractor, EP+S of Vermont reported finding SHPX 208564, a residue, UN1987, Alcohols, N.O.S. tank car with a less than tool tight vapor valve assembly, releasing vapors.  This valve assembly is mounted to a welded pipe nipple on the valve housing plate which was found during a follow-up inspection from defects that where noted on other tank cars of a unit train, inspected by FRA HM Inspector D. Tetterton. EP+S of Vermont tightened the vapor valve assembly securing the vapor release. Chemtrec was notified, report # 2012-07-17-00203. The issue identified and corrective action was communicated to consignee Aberdeen Energy, LLC., Mr. Bert Magstadt, 605-882-8480. This incident DID require a special switch move.    NARRI 5x(4+3+0)x(2+0) = 70  Cause Code: 361

column168: Barton Solvents delivered appx. 1660 gallons of petroleum solvent into 4 - 550 gallons IBC's on Eagle Window and Door property on 07-27-2012.  Communication about the gage readings between Eagle employees and the Barton driver was delayed briefly when the tanks were filled causing between 5 and 10 gallons of solvent to run into the vent piping and spill onto a concrete pad outside the building.  Some of the solvent ran onto dirt around the concrete pad.  Eagle Window employees collected the dirt and will dispose of it according to regulations.  They also called the DNR to file a report themselves.
column169: Better communication on how much will fit into the tanks prior to unloading and better communication between parties involved with unloading between Eagle Window and Barton Solvents during the unloading process.

column168: At approximately 02:05 hrs (Eastern Daylight Time) on July 11, 2012 NS train 186L809, traveling eastbound derailed on the Sandusky District at Milepost S2+1032ft.  The train consisted of 2 locomotives, 97 loaded freight cars and one empty freight car.    The 3rd through 19th cars derailed for a total of 17 cars derailed.  The 12th through 14th cars contained denatured ethanol, which were breached, released product, and caught fire.    There were two NRC reports made by Norfolk Southern.  NRC Report 1017364, made at 03:53 hrs on 7/11/2012, reported the incident time as 02:05hrs.  NRC Report 1017451, made at 16:16 hrs on 7/11/2012 updated the original report to include an evacuation and confirm the fact that hazardous materials had been released.     Approximately 100 people were evacuated for up to 12.5 hours and the initial evacuation radius was 1 mile.  The initial evacuation area included the area from 17th Avenue (north boundary) to 5th Avenue (south boundary) and from Essex Avenue (east boundary) to 6th Street (west boundary) was evacuated from approximately 2:30am until 10:00am.  At 10:00am the fire department reduced the evacuation area to include only 11th Avenue (north boundary) to 5th Avenue (south boundary) and to Fields Avenue (east boundary) to Grant Street (west boundary).  The residents in this area remained out of their homes until 3:00pm.  Everyone was able to return home at 3:00pm.     No train crew members were injured; however, there were 2 citizens that sustained alleged minor thermal burns while attempting to view the derailment.    Hazmat tank cars involved:                             Gallon        Gallons     Gallons  Reporting Mark     Capacity     in Car       Released/burned     Damage  NATX 354017        30,067       28,440      23,740                    Thermal rupture in shell  NATX 364083        30,046       28,457      21,457                    Head puncture  NATX 364118        30,078       20,550       7,850                    Thermal rupture in shell    Total estimated quantity ethanol released: 53,047 gallons.    NTSB is currently conducting an investigation of this incident.
column169: Norfolk Southern recommends that DOT minimum packaging for ethanol tank cars be improved to require thicker tanks, full height head shields, jackets, and thermal protection to These improvements would provide better puncture resistance and more time to take defensive actions to reduce the opportunity for thermal ruptures.

column168: Haz-mat vehicle was west bound on U.S. 64 in position to turn south on to U.S. 283.  Dodge pickup was East bound on U.S. 64 approaching the U.S. 283 JCT.  For an unknown reason Haz-mat vehicle driver failed to see Dodge pickup, and turned in front of Dodge pickup.  Dodge pickup could not avoid collision.  Dodge pickup struck haz-mat vehicle in the passenger side fuel tank.  The fuel tank on haz-mat vehicle ruptured and ignited causing both vehicles involved to burn.  The haz-mat vehicle driver exited his vehicle and accessed his fire extinguisher and observed the passenger of pickup trying to exit the vehicle.  The hazmat vehicle driver utilized his fire extinguisher to try to hold the flames at bay and simultaneously help the passenger out of the vehicle.  After helping the passenger from the Dodge pickup, the haz-mat driver fully exhausted his fire extinguisher, and was unable to reach the driver who was apparently critically injured and pinned in the collision.  The fire department arrived and extricated the driver of the Dodge pickup using the jaws of life.  The fire department extinguished the fire and kept the cargo tank cool with water.  No product was released from the cargo tank as a result of the accident or fire, but the cargo tank was damaged.
column169: The cause of this incident is currently under investigation.  Actions taken to prevent a future incident of similar nature is yet to be determined.

column168: THE TRAILER BEGAN LOADED WITH THE MATERIAL ON JULY 5, 2012. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS FULL IT WAS BROUGHT OVER TO THE HERITAGE TRANSPORT, LLC 10-DAY LOT ON JULY 9, 2012. THE LOAD WAS SCHEDULED TO BE TRANSPORTED TO THE TSD. HERITAGE-WTI ON JULY 17, 2012. THE TRAILER, 41-57 WAS BROUGHT OVER TO THE 10-DAY IN THE AFTERNOON OF JULY 9, 2012 AND PARKED IN THE OVERFLOW LOT OF THE 10-DAY. THE TRAILER WAS PARKED IN BETWEEN TWO EMPTY VAN TRAILERS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 AM ON JULY 10, 2012, HERITAGE TRANSPORT DRIVER DENNIS SHIRAR NOTICED THE FLAMES. DENNIS CONTACTED 911 AND REPORT THE FIRE. DENNIS PROCEEDED TO GATHER THE PAPERWORK, MANIFEST AND STOP TICKET FOR THE LOAD AND WAS ON SITE WHEN THE WAYNE TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED.  ONCE THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, AN EMPLOYEE OF HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE TRAILER OUT OF THE PARKING SLOT AND INTO THE MIDDLE OF PARKING LOT SO IT WAS MORE EASILY ASSESSABLE. THE FIRE DEPARMENT PERSONNEL REMAINED ON THE SCENE UNTIL THE FIRE WAS COMPLETELY EXTINGUISHED DEPARTING AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 A.M. DR. AMADA SHIRAR OF THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH WAS ON SITE TO INSPECT THE AREA AND TO DETERMINE WHETHER THERE WAS A RELEASE TO ANY WATERWAYS. DR. SHIRAR WAS SATISFIED THAT THERE WAS NOT A RELEASE TO ANY WATERWAYS.  ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC (ERS) WAS CONTACTED TO CONDUCT THE CLEAN UP OF THE FIRE AND THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER. THE CREW FOR ERS WAS ON SITE BY 7:00 AM. AND BEGAN THE PROCESS OF REMOVING THE MATERIALS FROM THE DUMP TRAILER. (PICTURES ATTACHED) THE CREW FIRST DRAINED ALL THE EXCESS WATER THAT ACCUMULATED IN THE DUMP TRAILER BY GATHERING THE LIQUIDS IN DRUMS AND INTO A VAC TANKER. THE MATERIALS FROM THE DUMP TRAILER WERE THEN TRANSFERRED TO A ROLL OFF BOX. THE GRAVEL AREA AFFECTED BY THE FIRE WAS SAMPLED AND THE GRAVEL GATHERED AND PLACED INTO A ROLL OFF BOX TO BE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
column169: AT THE PRESENT TIME, HERITAGE PERSONNEL ARE STILL CONDUCTING AN INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE FIRE IN THE TRAILER. ALL PROCESSES AND MATERIALS ARE BEING EVALUATED. THE GOAL IS TO PREVENT ANOTHER OCCURRENCE WITH THIS WASTESTREAM. ADDITIONAL REPORTS WILL BE FIELD ONCE ALL THE INFORMATION IS GATHERED AND EXAMINED.

column168: 7/31/2012: At approximately 2pm, a Conrail Signal Maintainer working in Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ detected an odor of gas.  Four tank cars containing the residue of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied were noted on a track in close proximity to where he was located.  CR Risk Manager A. Richter notified by Pavonia Yardmaster.    Upon arrival at yard office, a yard conductor moving locomotives in same area also noted similiar odor of gas.  Further inspection of all four LPG tank cars by CR's Richter noted tank car GATX 209470, containing the residue of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied (Butane), was leaking vapor by the "B" end liquid valve due to the valve not being completely closed; and, the closure plug for said valve not being even hand tight.  Valve closed and closure plug made tool tight by CR's Richter.  Car okayed for movement to final destination.      A green seal, marked as "INERGY-SJT 0002326" was noted laying alongside the outside of the protective housing.  However, no evidence that it was applied at one time and cut, tampered or removed to gain access to the valves inside the housing.  The seal was in "new" condition when examined.  It appears the seal was never applied to the protective housing prior to shipment.    NOTE: The other 3 tank cars containing residue of LPG (GATX 203075, NATX 400366 and GATX 30664) were all noted to have been sealed with similar seals noted on the unsecured seal of the leaking tank car.  Seals were not broken during this inspection and valves were examined/inspected through the protective housing port covers and the flap over the pressure relief device.  No exceptions or gas odor detected on these cars.

column168: On July 30, 2012, at 0920 hours, a CSXT train crew was instructed to switch rail cars inside the Alumax facility in Mount Holly, South Carolina.  The train crew was in the process of placing cars on the facilities pipeline stanchion track and inadvertently moved tank car   GATX 60730 a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Material, N.O.S.  This tank car was connected and was in the process of being off-loaded at the time.  The connection line stretched and subsequently failed resulting in the release of approximately 2,000 gallons of product.  Alumax management initiated their emergency action plan, completed state and federal notifications, and contacted Moran Environmental for remediation assistance.  CSX contacted Chemtrec, report number 2012-07-30-00108, to notify the shipper, Koppers.   Information in regards to the release was communicated to Koppers representative Barb Olzewski at 412-227-2874.      NARRI 5x(5+1+0) x (5+0) = 150   Cause Code: 662
column169: Prior to releasing a track to the railroad, ensure that facility personnel comply with standard operating procedures which include removing the tank car connected sign, removing any positive protection to the track structure, and ensuring that all rail cars on the track are properly secured. column168: THE TRUCK WAS LEAVING TOWN OF CRAWFORD, NE ON HWY 20 AND STARTED AROUND A SWEEPING CURVE. IT TRAVELING AT 35-40 MPH AND STARTED TO ACCELERATE TO THE NEW SPEED LIMIT OF 65 MPH WHEN THE TRAILER CAME AROUND CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. THE TRAILER BROKE AWAY FROM THE TRUCK AND FLIPPED. THE TRUCK WAS PULLED OVER ON IT'S SIDE AS THE TRAILER BROKE AWAY. TWO 330 GALLON IBC TOTES OF 25% (WT) HYDROCHLORIC ACID WERE ON THE TRAILER. AROUND 300 TO 330 GALLONS OF HC1 LEAKED OUT ON THE GROUND. THE REST WAS CONTAINED AND TRANSFERRED TO EMPTY IBC CONTAINERS THAT WERE LOCATED ON A SECOND TRUCK THAT WAS UNINVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE CRASH SITE AND NEUTRALIZED WITH 6 SACKS OF SODA ASH. THE SOIL WILL BE RECOVERED AND REPLACED UNDER THE SUPERVISOR OF TERRA TECH PER NE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (REPORT NO. 070712-SM-1224) THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE A LIGHT MISTING RAIN THAT MADE THE PAVEMENT SLICK. EMS PERSONNEL AT THE SITE SAID THAT THERE HAD BEEN A NUMBER OF ACCIDENTS AT THIS LOCATION WHEN THE PAVEMENT IS WET.
column169: IN THE FUTURE THE DRIVER WILL WAIT UNTIL HE IS OUT OF THE CURVE AND BACK ONTO THE STRAIGHT AWAY BEFORE BEGINNING TO ACCELERATE. HE FEELS THE COMBINATION OF SLICK PAVEMENT, THE SWEEPING CURVE AND THE ACCELERATION CAUSED THE TRAILER TO START TO HYDROPLANE. BY THE TIME HE REALIZED WHAT WAS HAPPENING THE TRAILER WAS ALREADY PULLING THE TRUCK SIDEWAYS. IN ADDITION THE DRIVER WILL BE REQUIRED TO TAKE COURSES IN 'DECISION DRIVER TRAINING", "LIGHT VEHICLE ROLLOVER' AND DO A COMMENTARY DRIVE.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car (SHPX 204898) was reported leaking from the man way in the Valley Park Yard located in Shakopee, MN. The car was immediately stopped from further movement and isolated until Randy Rowe, ERCO Worldwide (Shipper), was on-site. The release was stopped as the car was now idle. Upon Mr. Rowe's arrival it was discovered that the evidence bag over the man way had a cut strap and the security seal was displaced. The bag was removed (suspected vandalism) and it was found that the pressure release device (Girard RR407) was unbolted from the flange allowing product to escape. The valve was remounted and the evidence bag replaced. An estimated one gallon was released to the side of the car and surrounding ballast. The product was neutralized for remediation activities.
column169: This incident is a result of tampering - all measures were taken to prevent human error. However as always inspect fittings and securements prior to transportation.

One (1) 55-gallon drum of spent absorbents, and two (2) 55-gallon drums of liquid wash water were generated during the cleanup. column168: Tank car UTLX 210918 (loaded) was found to be improperly secured with one man-way swing bolt less then tool tight. Upon further inspection product was visibly dripping from man- way lid. column42: EXPLOSIVE, BLASTING, TYPE E OR EXPLOSIVE, AGENT BLASTING, TYPE E
column168: After driving approximately 20 miles from the Shipper, our driver was notified by another motorist that product was spilling from the trailer.  Our driver inspected the trailer and confirmed that a cleanout port cap (cover) on the top of the trailer had become dislodged and was hanging by its tether.  He contacted QC's 24/7 response center, who dispatched a hazardous material contractor to the site.  As the port is at the top of the tank, product ceased spilling when the trailer was stationary and level.  The contractor cleaned the product from the trailer and the highway.  The cover was replaced, and secured.     Investigation revealed that the shipper had installed a cam-lock fitting on a cleanout port to facilitate loading, and closed the opening with a cam-lock cover.  Procedure was to load, replace the cover and seal the ears in the closed position, which provides a secondary lock to the cover.  The fitting is no longer being used for loading, so the seal application was no longer part of the loading procedure.  The seal had been removed at some time prior to this shipment, and road vibration appears to have allowed the cover ears to move, dislodging the cover from the trailer.
column169: The cam-lock fittings will be replaced with conventional threaded cleanout caps.  Caps will be installed and torqued to manufacturer's specifications.

THE SECURITY GUARD CONTACTED THE IMTT  FIRE DEPARMENT WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THEY ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 CUPS OF MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED INTO THE TANK CRASH BOX. THEY CONTACTED IMTT'S IN-HOUSE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, EQ NORTHEAST, TO WIPE DOWN THE CRASH BOX AND TO CLEAN UP TH SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT HAD DRIPPED ONTO THE PAVEMENT. THEY ESCORTED THE DRIVER BACK TO IMTT WHERE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DOME COVER GASKET WAS MISSING. THE CARRIER DISPATCHED A MECHANIC TO IMTT WITH A DOME COVER GASKET WHICH HE INSTALLED. THE DRIVER WAS THEN PERMITTED TO LEAVE THE FACILITY.
column169: During the investigation into this incident, the driver admitted that he did not check the dome cover to insure that a gasket was in place. The driver was suspended from work and thoroughly retrained on proper pre-trip inspection procedures.

column168: At 0520 on 7/13/12, a transloading employee at the TRANSFLO- General Products terminal in Charlotte, NC was preparing to transload liquid asphalt from a railcar to a truck. As the employee was opening the product valve on a railcar (# UTLX 75418), approximately 10 gallons of liquid asphalt spewed out of the false dome lid opening, ran down the railcar sides, and dripped into the ballast between the rails and also onto the asphalt road in-between rail tracks. Pressure built up in the railcar from heating the railcar with steam lines. The steam was immediately shut-off to the railcar. Upon further investigation, it has been determined that pressure built up in the railcar due to a leak in the product hose line trace. After product cooled, it was scraped off the asphalt and ballast and disposed of.
column169: The asphalt product hose was replaced with a new more durable hose. Transload employees were instructed to increase diligence when inspecting product hoses before use for any signs or leaks from the product hose. Product hoses will be replaced upon any signs of wear, tear, or any type of deterioration. More frequent inspections will ensure product hoses are replaced before they fail due to deterioration.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: While transferring liquid asphalt from truck into a railcar (# UTLX 670762) the transloading employee at the Birmingham TRANSFLO terminal was monitoring the floating gauge system that was being utilized to determine when to stop this transfer. The visual inspection of the floating gauge showed the float was still all the way down indicating there was plenty of room left in the railcar for liquid asphalt to be loaded. As the load proceeded longer than normal, the TRANSFLO manager climbed up on top of the railcar to visually check the volume of liquid asphalt that had been loaded into the railcar. As he got to the second rung from the top of the railcar, liquid asphalt started coming out of the top of the railcar. The floating gauge had failed to operate as designed. The pump was shut off immediately, but about 20 gallons of liquid asphalt was released from the railcar due to overfilling the package. There were no injuries to manager climbing the railcar and no drains were impacted. The release was completely contained. Once asphalt cooled and solidified, it was immediately cleaned up and properly disposed of.
column169: The float system devised for use on this transfer was not a proven monitoring method. The float system failed to function as it was intended. The float system was the only means to gauge outage on this transfer.    Actions Taken:  1)A new metered pump has been ordered for this transfer and will be put into service when received.   2) The terminal will continue to only place three trailer loads into railcar until other method can be proven to measure outage, in addition to use of the metered pump.

column168: I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL WITH MY PPE ON.  WHEN I GOT TO THE SLIDE I NOTICED A STRONG ODOR AND PUT ON MY MASK.  USING THE DECISION TREE I TOLD THE SUP TO EVACUATE THE SLIDE.  WHEN I FOUND THE SPILL I DETERMINED IT WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND WENT TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  I NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL ON THE SLIDE AND PICKED UP BROKEN GLASS AND PUT IT IN A SPILL TUB.  I SEPERATED THE SPILLED-ON PACKAGES AND PUT THEM ON A CART.  I POURED WATER ON THE SLIDE AND SODIUM BICARBONATE.  USING A BROOM I NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AND SWEPT THE RESIDUE TO THE BOTTOM.  I THEN USED A WET WIPE WITH SODIUM BICARB ON IT AND WIPED THE SLIDE DOWN.

column168: THIS IS A WRITTEN REPORT OF THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 5,625 POUNDS OF 98% SULFURIC ACID FROM A RAILCAR (KCCX 3258) AT SIMPLOT PHOSPHATES ON JULY 30, 2012, AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 P.M. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN SIMPLOT EMPLOYEES WERE OFF LOADING SULFURIC ACID FROM THE RAILCAR. AN OPERATOR ATTACHED THE AIR FITTING AND UNLOADING FITTINGS TO THE RAILCAR TO UNLOAD THE CAR INTO A SULFURIC ACID STORAGE TANK T-115. AIR PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO THE RAILCAR TO PUSH ACID OUT OF THE RAILCAR TO THE STORAGE TANK. THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE RAILCAR UNLOADING HOSE WAS OPENED AND ACID STARTED TO FLOW.  THE OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY NOTICED A LEAK BETWEEN SIMPLOT'S UNLOADING HOSE FITTING AND THE FITTING ON THE RAILCAR. THE OPERATOR SHUT OFF THE AIR SUPPLY TO THE RAILCAR BUT DID NOT BLEED THE PRESSURE OFF THE CAR. HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE FITTING TO STOP THE LEAK, THE FITTING CAME OFF THE RAILCAR UNLOADING STATION. THIS CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AND WYOMING DEPARTMENT OF WATER QUALITY (WDEQ)WERE NOTIFIED SHORTLY AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.    THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED TWO CAUSES FOR THIS INCIDENT. FIRST, THE OPERATOR SHOULD NOT HAVE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE ACID FITTING WHILE THE RAILCAR WAS PRESSURIZED. SECOND, THE THREADS ON THE UNLOADING FITTING THAT THE SIMPLOT EMPLOYEE USED TO CONNECT THE UNLOADING HOSE TO THE RAILCAR WERE WORN AND DID NOT ALLOW THE FITTING TO BE TIGHTENED. THE WORN FITTING WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE. (THE FITTINGS ON THE RAILCAR WERE IN GOOD CONDITION IT WAS THE SIMPLOT INSTALLED FITTING THAT HAD THE WORN THREADS AND THAT IS THE FITTING THAT FAILED). TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, SIMPLOT IS REVIEWING THE INCIDENT WITH ALL OF THE RAIL YARD EMPLOYEES AND IS EVALUATION A PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE PROGRAM TO THE UNLOADING FITTINGS.

column168: A forty foot intermodal container HJCU 143555 was reported leaking after its arrival on a BNSF intermodal train. A container below HJCU 143555's position was wet with liquid that escaped from HJCU 143555. HJCU 143555 was grounded trackside over protective sheeting. Contract responders opened HJCU 143555 to ventilate it before entry and observed the interior lading had shifted. Three 55 gallon steel drums were found leaking at their sidewalls from contact with shifted lading due to insufficient blocking and bracing. The damaged drums were placed into overpack drums. HJCU 143555's interior was cleaned of spillage, along with the exterior of the other impacted container. Afterwards, all lading was returned inside HJCU 143555 properly blocked and braced for further transportation.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process includes adherence to acceptable containerized loading patterns with appropriate blocking and bracing to eliminate longitudinal and lateral lading shifts.

column168: The pallet was loaded and the trailer was closed.  It was discovered that the trailer was leaking afterwards.  We pulled the pallet out of the trailer (4 drums on one pallet), it was on the floor on the right side next to the other pallets of drums in the order.  We lifted the pallet up and Supervisor saw that one of the drums had slid into the corner of one of the pieces of wood that made up the bottom of the pallet.  The drum was indented at the point where it was clearly pinched into the bottom of the pallet, and there was a pen sized hole that was leaking; it might have been 15-20 minutes before it was discovered.  Supervisor determined that, while loading, the drum that was leaking had managed to shift just slightly enough to get pinched into the bottom of the pallet.  Supervisor looked to see if there was any way a fork lift blade could have sneaked up there, but that didn't look possible.  Also, the drum was clearly wedged into the bottom of the pallet where it was leaking.  This was in no way the fault of the loader, and the shipper didn't do anything negligent either.  Somehow the drum, which had come back to our dock without leaking, had managed to rub against the edge of the bottom piece of wood on the pallet enough to cause a puncture.  Since the pallet was leaking onto the dock after it was pulled out, Supervisor immediately had it loaded into a haz-mat container to minimize the spillage.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the TA Truck Stop, the driver noticed free liquid leaking from the tractor.  Chemtron Corporation of Avon, Ohio was dispatched to inspect the trailer and perform the cleanup.  Chemtron Corporation offloaded the trailer and discovered one (1) leaking steel drum.  Approximately 15 gallons of free liquid were released.  The release was the result of two small holes on the bottom of the drum.  Chemtron Corporation performed the cleanup using absorbent pads.  The cleanup materials and leaking drum were placed into one (1) 85-gallon plastic overpack drum, which was loaded onto the trailer.  The manifest was amended and the waste was transported to the disposal facility.
column169: No plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Franks Vacuum Truck Service will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Tank car UTLX 201753 standing on the repair track awaiting wheel work was reported with a fresh product stain on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure.  A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 201753. Intact manway shipper seal Gallup Refinery 2416 was removed and all manway securement bolts were found tool tight. Further inspection into the condition of the manway gasket revealed the applied gasket was aged and compressed, thus not providing a good closure seal.  A new manway gasket was installed; all manway securement bolts were tool tightened and BNSF seal numbered 06157586 applied at the manway. Afterwards, no further product spillage was observed at the repair track and during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Lone Star Trucking LLC LPG transport trailer #432 (cargo tank serial number 121708) started loading Liquefied petroleum gas at 1415 on 07/20/2012.  At 1444 the driver heard a noise from the top of the trailer and determined that the pressure relief valve was lifting.  Facility personnel were notified immediately and responded by securing the area and monitoring with a 4-gas monitor. The atmosphere surrounding the cargo tank was determined to be safe to transfer the LPG liquid back to its source. The product loaded on the trailer was immediately transferred to the origin facility using the liquid pump on the LPG transport.  After removing the LPG from the cargo tank,  the relief valve reseated and the transport was removed from the scene. Upon removal from the cargo tank,  the failed pressure relief valve was found to have several cracks in the operating spring.  The valve had been installed originally in June 2009 and was expected to work without failure for at least 5 years.  As a rule,  Lone Star Trucking LLC replaces cargo tank relief valves every 5 years coinciding with the cargo tank hydrostatic testing.

column168: A SEMI-TRACTOR PULLING A TRANSPORT TANKER CARRYING 5500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WITH 10% ETHANOL AND 2000 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 435 IN KANSAS CITY MO AT APPX 1:36AM ON 7/14/12. AS HE APPROACHED THE OVERPASS FOR STATELINE ROAD SEPARATING MISSOURI AND KANSAS HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS TRACTOR AND STRUCK THE METAL GUARDRAIL WITH THE PASSENGER SIDE OF HIS TRACTOR AND TRAILER.  HE CONTINUED ACROSS THE OVERPASS AND AFTER CLEARING THE BRIDGE THE TRACTOR THEN PULLED TO THE RIGHT AND THE TRACTOR TRAILER LEFT THE ROADWAY TRAVELED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT AND OVERTURNED. ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING WB ON INTERSTATE 435 STOPPED AND CALLED 911 TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT. POLICE OFFICERS FROM LEAWOOD KS WERE DISPATCHED AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPX 1:39AM AND FOUND THE DRIVER HAD BEEN THROWN FROM THE TRACTOR CABE AND WAS LYING NEXT TO THE TRACTOR WHICH HAD SEPARTATED FROM THE TRAILER. THEY REMOVED HIM FROM THE AREA AND WAITED FOR LEAWOOD KANSAS FD PERSONAL WHICH ARRIVED AT APPX 1:43AM. LEAWOOD FD PROVIDE ON-SCENE MEDICAL TREATMENT AND TRANSPORTED THE INJURED DRIVER TO OVERLAND PARK KANSAS REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER. LEAWOOD FD IDENTIFIED FUEL LEAKING FROM THE #3 COMPARTMENT ON THE TRAILER (LAYING ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE) COMING FROM THE TOP HATCH AND ALSO FROM THE TRACTORS RUPTURED SADDLE TANK (LAYING ON ITS DRIVER SIDE). THEY PLACED ABSORBENT BOOMS DOWN HILL FROM THE TRAILER AND THE TRACTOR. HAZMAT RESPONSE OF OLATHE KS WAS CONTRACTED BY CARTER ENERGY TO CUT HOLES IN EACH OF THE 4 TRAILER COMPARTMENTS TO REMOVE THE FUEL (STARTING WITH COMPARTMENT #3). PUMP OUT STARTED AT 7AM. CREWS FOUND THAT THE FRONT END OF THE #1 COMPARTMENT HAD SPLIT (UNSEEN FROM OUTSIDE) LOSS OF APPX 1975G OF DF. PUMP OUT CONCLUDED AT 8:45AM. JOHNSON COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL DIRECTED CARTER ENERGY TO BEGIN SITE REMEDIATION EFFORTS IMMEDIATELY WHICH INCLUDED SOIL CONTAMINATION REMOVAL, DISPOSAL, TESTING AND FINALLY REFILL/OVERSEEDING BY HAZMAT RESPONSE INC. JOHNSON COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL AND KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT HAVE OVERSEEN THE REMEDIATIOIN PROJECT. ESTIMATED COMPLETION DATE IS 8/15/12

LEAVE YOURSELF AN OUT 5. MAKE SURE THEY SEE YOU.    CONTINUE TO MONITOR ALL DRIVERS PERFORMANCE USING (MOBIUS ON BOARD COMPUTER SYSTEMS) AND UTILIZE THE (DRIVER ALERT HIGHWAY MONITORING PROGRAM). column168: A COMPANY DRIVER INADVERTENTLY TRANSPORTED 100 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS N.O.S. CONTAMINATED WITH BENZENE AND ARSENIC THINKING IT WAS NON-HAZARDOUS BRINE WATER FROM ONE DOMINION TRANSMISSION INC., (DTI) FACILITY TO ANOTHER DTI FACILITY. THIS SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS MADE WITHOUT A MANIFEST AND AS SUCH WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE AND THE SHIPMENT WAS UNLOADED INTO 25,000 GALLON BRINE WATER TANK CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 5400 GALLONS OF BRINE WATER. UPON DISCOVERY THE BRINE TANK WAS LOCKED OUT TO PREVENT FURTHER ADDITION OF LIQUID INTO THE TANK. ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES IN NEW YORK AND PENNSYLVANIA WERE CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT. THE CONTENTS OF THE BRINE WATER TANK WERE UNLOADED AND SHIPPED AS A PROPERLY MANIFESTED HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE TANK WAS CLEANED AS WELL AS THE CARGO TANK THAT HAULED THE UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE RINSATE WAS SHIPPED AS A MANIFESTED HAZARDOUS WASTE. BOTH SHIPMENTS WERE SENT TO CLEAN HARBOR (EPA ID# MDD98055189) TSDF IN BALTIMORE, MD.
column169: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE PREVIOUS SHIPMENTS FROM THIS SITE HAD CONSISTED ONLY OF NON-HAZARDOUS WASTEWATER, AND THE DRIVER DID NOT REALIZE THAT THIS SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID. HE AND OTHER DRIVERS WHO MAY HAUL NON-HAZARDOUS WASTEWATER WERE GIVEN A HAZMAT AWARENESS REFRESHER PRESENTATION. THIS PRESENTATION INCLUDED A REVIEW OF LABELS AND MARKINGS AS WELL AS A REVIEW OF WHAT PAPERWORK IS REQUIRED IF THEY HAUL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. AS A BEST MANAGEMENT PRACTICE THE DRIVERS WILL BE REQUIRED TO REVIEW THE MATERIAL TO BE TRANSPORTED AND CONTACT DOMINION’S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DEPARTMENT FOR GUIDANCE IF THEY HAVE ANY DOUBTS OR QUESTIONS ABOUT THE MATERIAL TO BE TRANSPORTED. THEY WERE ALSO INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT DOMINION’S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DEPARTMENT IF THEY ARE IN AREAS THAT THEY DO NOT NORMALLY HAUL WASTE LIQUIDS.

column168: V#1 OUR INSURED UNDER DISPATCH IS EN ROUTE I-75 S/B MM 215 TO TAKE A LOADED CONTAINER/CHASSIS SET UP TO THE SAVANNAH GA PORT FOR EXPORT.  CONTAINER CONTAINED UN1866 & UN3082 CLASS 3 & CLASS 9.     OUR LIMITED UNDERSTANDING CURRENTLY IS THAT OUR TRACTOR TRAILER WAS FOLLOWING ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER, HE SAW SPARKS AND THEN A TIRE WHICH HE COULD NOT AVOID AND/OR ATTEMPTED EVASIVE ACTION CAUSING HIM TO ROLL OVER.  UNIT ROLLED ONTO GUARD RAIL WHICH TORE OPEN THE SIDES OF THE CONTAINER AND A FEW OF THE RIMS ON STEEL DRUMS ALLOWED LEAKAGE TO ROADWAY AND ONTO SHOULDER AND SOIL.     CURA EMERG SERVICES WAS CALLED 06:27 ONCE WE WERE ABLE TO OBTAIN A COPY OF THE WORK ORDER SO THAT WE KNEW WHAT PRODUCT WE WERE DEALING WITH, CHRIS WAS THE INCIDENT MGR ON CALL WHO CALLED SWS OUT OF ATLANTA TO RESPOND. LOCALLY THE FIRE CHIEF WAS ON SITE. JACKIE WITH GA STATE DEP CALLED TO CONFIRM A TEAM WAS EN ROUTE.  FEDERAL DEP CALLED TIM TO BE SURE I WAS HANDLING ACCIDENT BECAUSE OF COMPLAINT FROM JACKIE.  PEACH STATE ENVIRO RESPONSE WAS ON SITE AS WELL THROWING SAND ON ROADWAY SO THAT THEY COULD GET THE HWY REOPENED.    HENRY CTY POLICE DEPT RESPONDED P 770-288-8292 OFFICER INGRAM REPORT 12013610
column169: THIS PARTICULAR ACCIDENT WAS EXTRAORDINARY IN THE FACT THAT IT IS QUITE UNEXPECTED TO HAVE A TIRE SUDDENLY THROWN IN ONE'S PATH, HOWEVER WE DID REVIEW WITH DRIVER THE SMITH DEFENSIVE DRIVING SYSTEM, WHERE WE NOTE STAYING AWAY FROM TRAVELING WITH THE PACK, ALLOWING FOR MORE FOLLOWING DISTANCE AND CREATING A SPACE CUSHION FOR FINDING "AN OUT" TAKING EVASIVE ACTION.

A TRANSFLO transloading employee started a transload of Ferric Chloride load from railcar SHPX 207017 to Kunle Trailer#441. As the transfer was occurring the employee noticed a small drip of liquid at the trailer connection. The employee stopped the transfer process, and followed the standard operating procedure of blowing out the product hose going to the trailer. When the employee went to adjust the connection from the hose to the trailer unloading spout, liquid product was quickly released from the hose.  Upon review, it was determined the employee had failed to remove the bottom cap on the trailer unloading spout. This employee was new and despite being properly trained on this transfer, the employee failed to inspect the bottom cap of on the unloading spout to ensure the cap had been removed.  There was no damage or defects to the transfer hose or on either package (railcar or trailer). This release was caused by human error. No drains were impacted. The spill was contained, cleaned up, and properly disposed of.
column169: Corrective Actions:   1. Critical parts inspection: The caps were painted bright colors (orange) to help new transloading employees remember to visually inspect the bottom cap.  2. Training: All transload employees were re-trained on the inspection process to include proper cap placement.

column168: At 0615 on 7/26/12, a TRANSFLO terminal operator discovered that railcar UTLX 70826 was leaking asphalt out of the dome lid. It appears that the railcar had been overloaded with asphalt at its origin and when the railcar was heated with steam (prior to unloading) the product had expanded. Since the railcar has been overloaded, the expansion of asphalt during heating forced the asphalt out of the top dome lid that was vented. Approximately 15 gallons of asphalt ran down the side of the railcar and dripped onto the ground. Asphalt in tailcar was unloaded to a lower level to stop the leak. Asphalt on the ground and railcar was allowed to cool and then was scraped up and properly disposed of.
column169: The original shipper was notified that railcar had been loaded with an excessive amount product to allow for expansion when heated with steam prior to transfer. TRANSFLO is working with shipper to ensure railcar is shipped with a minimum level of outage to ensure product expansion will not result in a release. Also TRANSFLO operators will now visually check level of asphalt in the railcar prior to heating to ensure there is enough outage (headspace in railcar) to allow for product expansion. If enough headspace is not available railcar will not be heated with steam.

column168: 7/31/2012: At approximately 855pm, CR crew FC18 was switching cars into the Sunoco facility, Westville, NJ.  Conductor noted side of tank car UTLX 205156, load, Petroleum Crude Oil, wet.  As car was being spotted inside customer, the Conductor notified Sunoco's contract rail switcher, SMS via the conductor for SMS that was observing the move.  SMS advised they would handle.    Later inspection by SMS and Sunoco revealed a defective pressure relief device (reclosing-style).  Specifics not determined at this time.  Car has since been unloaded and is planned to have the pressure relief device replaced by mobile repair unit (inside the Sunoco facility).    Findings of inspection of valve when replaced will be submitted when known.

column168: DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON MN 4. HIGHWAY WAS RECENTLY RESURFACED AND ONLY HAD CENTER LINE STRIPING. NO OUTER LANE PAINT MARKINGS ON THE ROADWAY. SHOULDER HAD 3-4 INCH DROP OFF WITH NO SHOULDER GRAVEL REBUILD FROM THE RECENT RESURFACING. RELATIVELY NO FURTHER SHOULDER INTO THE DITCH. DRIVER APPRARENTLY DROPPED THE STEER TIRE OFF THE HIGHWAY AND ONTO THE SHOULDER. THE DRIVER COULD NOT RECOVER THE UNIT BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY WITH NO REBUILD OF GRAVEL ON THE SHOULDER AND THE SHALLOW SHOULDER AREA. THE UNIT OVERTURNED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE RIGHT OF WAY CAUSING UPSET OF THE UNITS CONTENTS. DRIVER WAS UNINJURED AND IMMEDIATELY CONTACT EMERGENCY PERSONNEL AND THE CARRIER. CARRIER CONTACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND LOCAL POLICE AGENCY.  EMEREGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FOUND MINOR AMOUNTS OF UN3260 (SULFURIC ACID) DRY FROM 5 GL PAILS DAMAGED IN THE OVERTURN AND ONE DRUM OF IODINE LEAKING. TOTAL VOLUME RELEASE 1-2 GALLONS. SORBENT PADS WERE USED TO CONTROL THE MINOR LEAKAGE IN THE TRAILER.  PACKAGE DAMAGE WAS CAUSED BY UPSET OF THE 5 GL. PAILS (DRUMS) SMACH INTO ONE ANOTHER. DRUM BUNG LEAKED FROM WEIGHT OF THE OTHER FREIGHT COLLIDING WITH IT.
column169: CARRIER IS CURRENTLY PROVIDING ALL DRIVERS INCIDENT REVIEW INFORMATION AND TRAINING, INCLUDING ACCIDENT AVOIDANCE MEASURES, EMERGENCY RESPONSE REVIEW, REVIEW OF LOAD SECUREMENT.    RECOMMENDATION FOR IMPROVED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRANSPORTATION IS POSSIBLE FURTHER SEPARATION OF SMALLER LESSOR CONTAINERS FROM LARGER CONTAINERS IN TRANSIT.

column168: Determined at consignee that the car had lost 29,000 pounds of ammonium nitrate somewhere between El Dorado, AR and the North Little Rock Port.  Product was found on the 100 lead and track 412 in the North Little Rock yard.  A sample was taken to the lab for ID purposes and a sample sent to El Dorado Chemical.  El Dorado Chemical confirmed the material was their Ammonium Nitrate that was lost and the lab confirmed the product found was ammonium nitrate.  A vacuum truck was utilized to collect the material from the track.  Once collected the material was denatured with 50/50 soil and product  and placed in a roll off box for disposal.  The car was located and placed in Bad Order status.  Inspection of the car revealed a bent operating arm on the left side of the car and a bowed slide door on the middle compartment.  The operating arm was difficult to operate and secure, and believed to be the compartment in question.  The car was "Home Shop - Do Not Load" for repairs.

A DELIVERY OF 15% HYDROCHLORIC ACID (HCL) WAS MADE FROM ONE BULK DELIVERY TRUCK TO ANOTHER BULK DELIVERY TRUCK PARKED ON THE YODER WELL PAD LOCATION. APPROXIMATELY 4700 GAL. OF PRODUCT (APPROXIMATELY 1700 GALLONS OF HCL AND 3000 GALLONS OF WATER) WAS RELEASED THROUGH A DISCONNECTED HOSE DUE TO A FLAPPER VALVE BEING LEFT PARTIALLY OPEN. THE RELEASE MIGRATED THROUGH A HOLE IN THE CONTAINMENT ON TO THE WELL PAD LOCATION THEN OVER AN EMBANKMENT INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH. THE RELEASE CONTINUTED DOWN A DRAINAGE DITCH AND COLLECTED AT A ROCK CONTAINMENT WALL WHERE A SMALL AMOUNT TRICKLED THROUGH AND INTO A WATERWAY OUTFALL.    UPON DISCOVERY, IMMEDIATE ACTIONS WERE TAKEN TO CONTAIN AND NEUTRALIZE THE HCL. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS WERE IMMEDIATELY MOBILIZED TO BEGIN CLEAN-UP EFFORTS. VACUUM TRUCKS WERE IMMEDIATELY UTILIZED TO COLLECT SPILLED MATERIAL AND AFFECTED SOIL AND WATER.
column169: ALL ACID TRANSPORTS HAVE BEEN INSPECTED TO ENSURE THAT THEY HAVE THE REQUIRED DOUBLE VALVES AND ALL HANDLES ARE IN PLACE AND FUNCTIONING PROPERLY.    IN THE FIELD WHEN PUMPING ACID, A SUPERVISOR WILL OVERSEE THE OPERATION.    ON ALL OPERATIONS WHERE THE CREW LEAVES LOCATION, THE HOSE WILL BE DISCONNECTED FROM BOTH THE ACID TRANSPORT AND BLENDER AND WILL REMAIN DISCONNECTED UNTIL THE CREW RESUMES NORMAL PUMPING ACTIVITIES. IN ADDITION, THE VALVE ON THE TRANSPORT WILL BE CAPPED SHUT.    GREATER EMPHASIS AND MANAGEMENT REVIEW HAS BEEN PLACED ON MANAGING ACID DELIVERIES.    EVERY CONNECTION IN THE ACID LINE SHALL HAVE CONTAINMENT.    WE HAVE DEVELOPED AND ADOPTED A WRITTEN PROCEDURE OUTLINING OUR PROCESS FOR TRANSFERRING ACID FROM THE ACID TRANSPORT TO THE BLENDER.

column168: DRIVER HAD JUST DELIVERD FUEL TO AN AGRICULTURE COMPANY AND WAS LEAVING THE AREA. TRUCK WAS MOVING ALONG A SINGLE LANE DIRT ROAD. DRIVER REPORTED THAT HE "MADE ROOM" ON THE ROAD FOR AN APPROACHING VEHICLE. DRIVER DID NOT REALIZED THE SOFTNESS OF THE SHOULDER WHICH RESULTING IN THE TANK TRUCK TO TRACK FURTHER OFF THE ROAD AND ROLLOVER DOWN AN EMBANKMENT INTO A DITCH (SEE ATTACHED PICTURES) AT APPROXIMATELY 1230 HOURS. EMBANKMENT WAS APPROXIMATELY 8 FEET BELOW ROAD GRADE AND STAGNANT WATER WAS PRESENT IN THE DITCH.  DRIVER WAS WEARING HIS SEAT BELT RESULTING IN NO INJURIES OR MEDICAL ATTENTION FOR THE DRIVER. AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, NO RELEASE OCCURRED FROM THE CARGO TANK OR LADING SYSTEM, EXCEPT FOR APPROXIMATELY 9 GALLONS OF CRANK/CASE MOTOR OIL AND SADDLE TANK FUEL. FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL, LEVY COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE, LEVY COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT, FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORATION AND ENVIRONMENTAL FOR ON-SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEANUP ALONG WITH UNIVERSITY TOWING FOR WRECKER SERVICE. WITHIN 2 HOURS OF THE ACCIDENT THE ACCIDENT'S PERIMETER WAS ENVIRONMENTAL SECURED AND WRECKER SERVICE HAD ALREADY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. WHEN EXTRACTING THE TANK TRUCK, ONE FUEL LINE ON THE LADING SYSTEM WAS CRACKED AND APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS WAS RELEASED FROM THAT LADING SYSTEM. AAG ENVIRONMENTAL IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED BY CLEANING UP THE RELEASE WHILE ALMOND OIL COMPANY PRO-ACTIVELY RESPONDED BY SECURING THE REMAINING 3 LADING SYSTEMS, BY CUTTING THE BELLY VALVE CABLES.    SEE ATTACHED ADDENDUM
column169: CHRIS ALMOND, VICE PRESIDENT, AND KEVIN HETHERINGTON, DIRECTOR OF OPERATIONS, HAVE MADE A COUPLE OF DECISIONS SINCE THIS INCIDENT.    1. WHILE OFF A PAVED SURFACE OUR TRUCKS WILL NOT BE BACKING UP OR SHARING A SINGLE LANE NON-PAVED ROAD WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE UNLESS ASSISTANCE IS PROVIDED OR AN OFFICER OF THE LAW DIRECTS OUR DRIVER/EQUIPMENT TO DO SO. IN THIS PARTICULAR SITUATION, OUR DRIVER SAID THAT ANOTHER CAR WAS COMING DOWN THE ROAD IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION. WHEN OUR DRIVER MOVED TO THE RIGHT TO MAKE ROOM FOR A MOTOR VEHICLE, HE HIT THE SOFT ROAD SHOULDER AND THUS THE ACCIDENT.  2. DUE TO THE REMOTE NATURE OF THIS LOCATION, OUR DRIVERS ALREADY CALL DISPATCH WHEN THE LOAD IS COMPLETE BUT NOW ALL DRIVERS WILL BE CONTACTING DISPATCH ONCE THE DRIVER IS ON A PAVED SURFACE.  3. IN THE EVENT OF A ROLLOVER, OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CUT THE BELLY VALVE CABLE LINES TO PERMANENTLY CLOSE THE TANK BELLY VALVE. ONLY IF WE ARE EXTRACTING FUEL FROM THE TANK WILL THOSE VALVES NOT BE CUT UNTIL AFTER THE FUEL HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TANK.

column168: SCOTT-GROSS CO., INC. DRIVER MR. MAUAL COCKRELL WAS DRIVING TRACTOR # 429755 TRAILER #307 (NON-SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK) TRAVELING ON US42 WEST (MI POINT #1.01), 8 MILES WEST OF WARSAW KY 41095.  MR. COCKRELL JUST DEPARTED FROM AIR LIQUIDE LARGE INDUSTRIES (6870 HWY 42 EAST, GHENT KY 41045) WHERE HE RECEIVED A LOAD (39886 LBS) OF UN1073 OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID 2.2 (5.1).  PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT MR. COCKRELL DESCRIBED A SUDDEN LUNGE (SURGE) FROM THE TRAILER CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO DRIFT TOWARDS THE OPPOSING LANE OF TRAFFIC.  MR. COCKRELL CORRECTED THE STEERING WHEN HE FELT THE TRAILER DISENGAGE FROM THE TRACTOR AND PUSH THE TRACTOR OFF THE HIGHWAY.  THE FIFTH WHEEL ON THE TRACTOR COMPLETELY BROKE LOOSE FROM THE TRAILER CAUSING THE TRACTOR TO ROLL OVER.  THE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT BROKE THE VENT PIPE ON THE NON-SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK CAUSING OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID TO DISPERSE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  MR. COCKRELL CONTACTED SCOTT-GROSS CO. REPRESENTATIVES AND THE LOCAL POLICE WHO RESPONDED AND CLOSED US42 FOR APPROXIMATELY 3.25 HOURS.  A SCOTT-GROSS TECHNICIAN ARRIVED ON SCENE AND WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAKING OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID FROM LEAKING THROUGH THE DAMAGED VENT PIPE.  THE ENTIRE LOAD OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID WAS EVENTUALLY RELEASED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE IN A CONTROLLED PROCESS BEFORE THE TRAILER WAS ERECTED RIGHT-SIDE UP USING A CRANE.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS TOWED FROM THE SCENE.
column169: Mr. Cockrell was interviewed by Scott-Gross personnel when he returned from the accident scene.  Mr. Cockrell was also sent for drug and alcohol testing - results were negative.  Although the accident is currently still being investigated, Scott-Gross Company, Inc, decided that Mr. Cockrell would participate in retraining on Pre-Trip and Post-Trip Inspections, and Safety and Awareness training pertaining to driving cargo tanks and preventing rollover accidents, and undergo a driver road test evaluation provided by his supervisor.

column168: PACKAGE FALURE: TRACTOR-TANKER TRAILER ROLLED OVER DUE TO UNKNOWN CAUSES. THERE WAS 5"X4" HOLE IN FRONT COMPARTMENT OF TANKER CAUSING 2,800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO LEAK OUT OF COMPARTMENT. THE FUEL LEAKED OUT OF THE TANKER COMPARTMENT IN APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR.    MITIGATIOIN ACTIONS; COLD TAPPING WAS PERFORMED ON TANKER COMPARTMENTS TO FACILITATE TRANSFER OF CONTAINED FUEL PRIOR TO UPRIGHTING TANKER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROX. 2800 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS RELEASED TO ROAD SIDE AND IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED BY VERY DRY SOIL UNDER TANKER, WITH NO POOLING OR RUN OFF OF FUEL.  EXCAVATION, TRANSPORTATION, DISPOSAL OF 294 TONS CONTAMINATED SOIL AS SPECIAL WASTE WAS COMPLETED. A SOIL VAPOR EXTRACTIOIN (SVE) HORIZONTAL TRENCH SYSTEM WAS INSTALLED TO ABATE GASOLINE IN AREAS NOT ACCESSIBLE FOR EXCAVATION. PERIODIC MONITORING OF SVE EXHAUST CONCENTRATIONS (RANGE FROM 429 TO 1020 PARTS PER MILLION). AS OF 8/28/12, EXHAUST VAPOR CONCENTRATIONS OF 731 PPM CONTRIBUTE TO INDICATE MASS REMOVAL IS OCCURRING. SOIL BORINGS WILL BE COMPLETED TO DETERMINE EXTENT OF RESIDUAL CONTAMINATION AS REQUIRED BY MDNR AFTER SVE MONITORING INDICATES EFFECTIVENESS IS DECLINING. CONTRACTOR IS WORKING WITH MDNR TO RESOLVE ANY ISSUES THAT MAY RESULT FROM THE RELEASE.
column169: ADDITIONAL ROLL-OVER PREVENTION DRIVER TRAINING. FOLLOW-UP DRIVER TRAINING FOR NARROW ROADWAY DRIVING.

column168: On July 30, 2012, Volcano Corporation contacted Expeditors-SFO to book services for nine boxes of cargo for international air transportation to Volcano Corporation in Alajuela, Costa Rica. The cargo in question contained 8 boxes of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. and 1 box of Environmentally Hazardous Substance liquid. The Shipper's  Dangerous Goods Declaration is attached as Exhibit A. Expeditors-SFO subcontracted a service provider (California Sierra Trucking) to pick up the cargo in question from Volcano Corporation's location for transfer to Expeditors-SFO's air cargo facility. At approximately 02:35 on July 31, 2012, California Sierra Trucking delivered the subject cargo to Expeditors-SFO's air cargo warehouse facility.  During the offload and freight check in process, 1 box of Petroleum Distillate, N.O.S., was accidentally dropped and the contents of the box leaked. Absorbent material was administered to prevent further spread of the dangerous material. Photographs of the spill are attached as Exhibit B. Following the spill, the emergency contact number on the Shipper's  Dangerous Goods Declaration  was called to seek guidance on next steps. A Dangerous Goods clean up company was recommended (Clean Harbors Environmental Services). Expeditors-SFO contacted Clean Harbors Environmental Services to schedule an appointment to have the spilled hazardous materials removed. The spilled Petroleum Distillate, N.O.S., was cleaned up on July 31, 2012.
column169: On July 31, 2012, both Expeditors-SFO  and Expeditors'  Corporate ("Expeditors-CHQ) management  were alerted of the situation. Expeditors does not package inner contents of Dangerous Goods and is not apprised with all ICAO technical requirements of the hazardous substance in question. Immediately following the discovery, Volcano Corporation's management  was contacted for a discussion about their hazardous materials procedures and dangerous goods packaging practices. During the hazmat removal process, Expeditors-SFO requested that Clean Harbors Environmental  Services review the inner contents of the box to  ensure that the declared packing instruction was followed. Upon review of the events leading up to hazardous materials spill, no extraordinary defects were discovered with the handling or with the packaging of the Dangerous Goods cargo. In an effort to lessen the possibility of reoccurrence, a discussion has been had with all dangerous goods certified warehouse employees to discuss the events of this hazardous spill and to reiterate the importance of careful handling of Dangerous Goods cargo.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: THE DRUM OF RESIN HAD BEEN LOADED INTO A TRAILER BY A DOCK WORKER. A SHORT TIME LATER A DIFFERENT DOCK WORKER PLACED MORE FREIGHT INTO THE TRAILER, PUSHING THE FREIGHT HE WAS LOADING FORWARD WHICH CAUSED IT TO COME INTO CONTACT WITH THE DRUM OF RESIN.    THE IMPACT CAUSED A RUPTURE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM NEAR THE BOTTOM AND THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM RAPIDLY.    THE SPILL WAS INITIALLY CONTAINED BY DOCK EMPLOYEES AND SUPERVISORS HOWEVER, THE FUMES WERE SUCH THAT SUPERVISORS DECIDED TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR ASSISTANCE.    THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND FURTHER CONTAINED THE SPILL, DISPERSED THE FUMES UNTIL THEY WERE NO LONGER A DANGER AND THEN DEPARTED THE SCENE. ENTIRE TIME FROM TIME OF SPILL UNTIL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LEFT WAS ABOUT 5 HOURS.    A HAZARDOUS CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP AND REMOVE THE MATERIAL.
column169: THE ACTIONS OF THE SECOND DOCK WORKER, THE PERSON THAT CAUSED THE DAMAGE, WERE CONTRARY TO COMPANY POLICY AND PROCEDURES REGARDING THE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE EMPLOYEE HAD RECEIVED TRAINING IN THE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WHICH HE DID NOT FOLLOW IN THIS SITUATION. THIS EMPLOYEE'S EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED AND THE FACTS OF THE SPILL WERE USED AT SUBSEQUENT SHIFT MEETINGS AS TRAINING.

column168: Leak discovered at Pilot Truck Stop off of I-40 exit 369, Knoxville, TN.  Driver notifies Con-way Freight Safety at approximately 0900.  Safety contacted ERTS to coordinate cleanup.  They dispatched SWS Environmental Services, Harriman, TN.  SWS was on scene at approximately 1100.  ERTS notified Tennessee Emergency management Agency (#1592) and NRC around 1000 prior to the arrival of the clean up crew.      Crew placed oil dry on the liquid that had spilled onto the ground, placed visqueen on the ground and unloaded the trailer onto it.  The last two pallets of product were shifted on the pallets.  One 5 gallon pail was empty.  One 5 gallon pail had one gallon in it. One 5 gallon pale was barely leaking but still mostly full.  Crew cleaned floor and placed waste material in 55 gallon drum, broke up saturated pallets and placed them in drum along with visqueen after reloading trailer.    It is estimated that all released material was recovered.  Impacted area: 20 square feet of trailer floor and asphalt parking lot.    It appears based on photos (spill team) and disposition paperwork from terminal, that the material released was not UN1760, Corrosive Liquids N.O.S. (sodium hydroxide), 8, II.  It appears to have been UN1760 Corrosive Liquids, N.O.S. (ethanolamine), 8, III.
column169: Follow up with shipper regarding shipment/shrinkwrap.  Proper securement retraining recommended for loader.

column168: Univar was being unloaded by Nisshinbo Automotive. The forklift operator was taking an IBC of H202 35% off the Univar trailer. While exiting the forklift operator had the IBC to high in the air.  As the forklift operator started over the dock ramp the IBC slid off the forks of the forklift and the container landed on the side splitting the container from the impact. The material flowed back into the trailer and all over the Univar drivers feet. The fire department flushed the material with water to neutralize the H202. The Univar driver was taken to the hospital with burns to his feet.
column169: Employees should not be allowed in trailers while forklifts are operating unless approved by a supervisor. Training for forklift operators on how to carry heavy liquid filled containers. Equipping forklifts with strapping devises to secure IBC containers. The IBC failed due to the impacked from being dropped.

column169: DRIVER WAS CONTACTED AND STOPPED, DOME LID WAS PROPERLY SEATED IN GROOVE ON DOME LID AND DOME LID WAS SECURELY FASTENED DOWN, STOPPING THE LEAK. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Traffic came to a sudden stop.  The driver applied the brakes but there was insufficient stopping distance.  The driver maneuvered the truck to avoid a collision and the trailer overturned during the maneuver.  Approximately 75 gallons of product leaked through the pressure relief valve because the trailer was on its side.  The local fire/EMS responded.  The trailer was uprighted and towed to the point of origin.  The product was cleaned up and removed from the roadway.  There were no injuries.  The roadway was closed for approximately 3 hours.
column169: The company provides training for Hazmat employees and drivers.  Training includes information on Hazmat incidents such as this one, to raise awareness and help prevent recurrences.  The driver involved in this incident was terminated for unsafe driving.

column168: Part VI: Description of Events & Package Failure    This load was originally loaded on Trailer No. LT-1255 at Chemical Reclamation Services in Avalon,TX on 07/24/2012 for delivery to Ash Grove Cement Co. in Foreman,AR. This truck and trailer driven by Driver Carl Parliament was involved in a traffic accident in Dallas, TX on 07/25/2012. The truck and trailer were rendered inoperable, and Triad Driver Ron Estep was dispatched to the accident scene to transfer the load to Trailer No. 129. This was done at the scene of the accident under the supervision of the Texas Highway Patrol,Harris Co.Sheriff Dept.,Dallas Fire Dept. HazMat Response Team, and Protect Environmental Services Inc. All valves, and dome lids were secured at the scene prior to leaving. This is a vacuum tank,and dome lids had to be secured in order to pull a vacuum and load the trailer. After transferring the load, Ron Estep continued on and delivered to Ash Grove Cement in Foreman,AR.    Mr.Estep delivered the load on 07/26/2012. Prior to unloading after arrival employees of Ash Grove Cement opened the dome lid on the tank,and took samples of the cargo. Apparently before moving the tank to the unloading area they did not secure the dome lid adequately,and when the driver braked,a small amount of product was sloshed out onto the pavement near the unloading area. Ash Grove Cement reported the spill to the National Response Center. They did not report it to Triad Transport, nor did the driver. The spill was cleaned up with absorbent,and was contained entirely to the concrete paved unloading area. This driver has resigned and no longer works for Triad Transport since then.    Triad Transport learned of the incident on 09/18/2012 when contacted by Gail Twitty of DOT, for follow up information. John Watkins,Safety Director from Triad Transport investigated and makes this report.
